elements.title: Olena Stepaniv (Wikipedia — did you know?)
elements.contents: ... that postcards were made of Olena Stepaniv (pictured) during the First World War, and in 1991 Lviv named a street after her?

elements.title: WIQT (Wikipedia — did you know?)
elements.contents: ... that radio station WIQT near Elmira, New York, was co-owned with a regional group of clothing, furniture, and shoe stores?

elements.title: Kitty Shiva Rao (Wikipedia — did you know?)
elements.contents: ... that Kitty Shiva Rao was the head of a committee to find out what Indian women wanted from the new Constitution of India?

elements.title: Eyes That Kiss in the Corners (Wikipedia — did you know?)
elements.contents: ... that the picture book Eyes That Kiss in the Corners was written to celebrate and empower Asian identities?

elements.title: Devonshire Close (Wikipedia — did you know?)
elements.contents: ... that access to London's Devonshire Close was restricted in order to avoid the wealthier streets surrounding it?

elements.title: Joseph Binder (Wikipedia — did you know?)
elements.contents: ... that Joseph Binder influenced modern poster design, creating posters for the 1939 New York World's Fair, the U.S. Army Corps and the American Red Cross?

elements.title: Elendil (Wikipedia — did you know?)
elements.contents: ... that J. R. R. Tolkien invented Elendil for a time-travel story, but ultimately included the character in his main Middle-earth mythology?

elements.title: Verdi Square (Wikipedia — did you know?)
elements.contents: ... that Verdi Square was originally a triangle?
